data.title: 'Oi, rusty face, where did you get the tan from?' How Britain's new top policeman was dubbed Sunbed Stephenson
data.meta_description: According to reports Sir Paul Stephenson's Rusty Face nickname started in his very first week in the Metropolitan Police Service, when he turned up at a charity function with a particularly deep tan.
data.text:
The appointment of Sir Paul Stephenson as Met Commissioner is truly a case of the future's bright, the future's orange.

The origins of his perma-tanned look have been the subject of amused debate since he arrived in London as deputy commissioner four years ago.

A glance through photographs taken since then may help explain why junior officers have dubbed him 'Rusty Face' or 'Sunbed Stephenson'.

Tan man: Sir Paul Stephenson (left) showing off his 'rusty face' look (left) and looking a little paler (right)

According to reports, the Rusty Face nickname started in his very first week in the Metropolitan Police Service, when he turned up at a charity function with a particularly deep tan.

The compere spotted Sir Paul in the crowd and, not realising who he was, made a joke about his appearance.

'Oi, rusty face, where did you get the tan from?' he inquired.

The vast majority of the crowd fell about laughing, unaware Sir Paul was the second most powerful man in the Met.

Last year, at a senior officer's retirement function, one eminent speaker joked: 'Over the years, Paul's attempts at self-defined ethnicity have been quite remarkable.'

Sir Paul took the remark in good part. Former Met chiefs have no doubt told him that a sense of humour is a prerequisite of the job.

The new Met boss yesterday vowed to end the celebrity culture at Scotland Yard.

Minutes after being confirmed as Metropolitan Police Commissioner, he made a thinly veiled swipe at his gaffe-prone predecessor Sir Ian Blair.

He said: 'It is not my aim to be boring. Neither is it my aim to be a celebrity. It is my intention to be a top-class police leader of the biggest police force in the UK and one of the best in the world.

'I want to be a police leader who people will follow out of more than just a mere sense of curiosity.'

In his four years in the job, Sir Ian became notorious for ill-judged public comments and was dogged by poor discipline and infighting among senior officers.

The country's highest-ranking Asian policeman, Tarique Ghaffur, controversial Met commander Ali Dizaei and the country's most senior openly gay officer, Brian Paddick, all challenged his authority.

But Sir Paul, 55, who was deputy to Sir Ian during most of his tenure, promised to pull the plug on the Yard soap opera.

Beaming with pride yesterday, the butcher's son from Lancashire set out the massive task he faces. He said his force must defy predictions that the recession will lead to soaring crime levels.

He also pledged that officers will continue with controversial tactics such as stop-and-search.

He said: 'Right at the top of our priorities continues to be protecting London from terrorism and continuing our national role in the wider counter-terrorism effort. That cannot slip down the list. It stands right at the top of priorities.

'Knife crime and kids murdering young people is up there with it. It is a huge priority here in London. We have shown a great deal of grit and decisive action around young people in knife crime and gangs in recent months and, while I'm far from complacent, that has been bearing some fruit.

'One of the key issues is keeping the communities on board to give us a mandate to go in there and use some pretty intrusive tactics to stop kids killing kids.'

Safe pair of hands: Sir Paul had an unblemished record until the arrest of Tory MP Damian Green (pictured)

The £253,000-a-year post became vacant a year earlier than expected following Sir Ian's resignation in October. He stepped down after London Mayor Boris Johnson said he no longer had confidence in him.

Sir Paul, former Lancashire chief constable and a married father of three, promised he would not be in thrall to politicians whether it be the Home Secretary or the Mayor of London.

'The idea of being beholden does not fit with my concept of leading a police force,' he said.

Home Secretary Jacqui Smith said: 'Sir Paul stood out at every stage in a long and testing process.

'He impressed me with his strong vision and approach to tackling the challenges that lie ahead.'

As head of Scotland Yard and its 53,000 staff, Sir Paul will become the country's most senior police officer, effectively in charge of fighting terrorism across the UK.

Sir Paul was the undisputed frontrunner for the job until the controversial arrest of Tory MP Damian Green in December while he was acting commissioner.

Fury greeted the decision to detain the Conservatives' immigration spokesman for nine hours while counter-terrorism officers raided his home and Commons office.

In the end his main challenger was Northern Ireland's top policeman Sir Hugh Orde.

The news of Sir Paul's promotion caps a career in the police which has spanned more than three decades.

Hired: Sir Paul Stephenson poses with London Mayor Boris Johnson (left) and Home Secretary Jacqui Smith (right) after being confirmed as the new Met Commissioner

Sir Paul joined Lancashire Constabulary in 1975 and was appointed to the rank of superintendent in February 1988.

After working in Lancashire and Northern Ireland, with the Royal Ulster Constabulary, he was appointed Assistant Chief Constable of Merseyside Police in October 1994.

His time there saw him leading high profile projects, including the reduction of gun crime and corruption, and efforts to combat terrorist activity.

In May 1999 he was appointed Deputy Chief Constable of Lancashire Constabulary.

Three years later he was promoted to Chief Constable of Lancashire, and he caught the eye of the Prime Minister of the time, Tony Blair, after dramatic improvements in his force's performance.

In March 2005, Sir Paul was appointed Deputy Commissioner of the Met, taking a largely behind-the-scenes - his critics would say anonymous - role in charge of strategy, organisational performance and diversity.

He received a knighthood in the Queen's Birthday Honours List of June 2008.

On December 1 last year Sir Paul became the Acting Commissioner of the Metropolitan Police after the dramatic resignation of Sir Ian Blair.

Sir Ian was forced to step down in October on the day the Daily Mail revealed he had used public funds to pay a close friend a five-figure sum for an image makeover.
